    {
      "id": "ml89h6od",
      "questionNumber": 8,
      "questionText": "<p>As compared with chlorocyclohexane, which of the following statements correctly apply to chlorobenzene?</p>\n<p>A. The magnitude of negative charge is more on chlorine atom.</p>\n<p>B. The $\\mathrm{C}-\\mathrm{Cl}$ bond has partial double bond character.</p>\n<p>C. $\\mathrm{C}-\\mathrm{Cl}$ bond is less polar.</p>\n<p>D. $\\mathrm{C}-\\mathrm{Cl}$ bond is longer due to repulsion between delocalised electrons of the aromatic ring and lone pairs of electrons of chlorine.</p>\n<p>E. The $\\mathrm{C}-\\mathrm{Cl}$ bond is formed using $\\mathrm{sp}^2$ hybridised orbital of carbon.</p>\n<p>Choose the correct answer from the options given below :</p>",
      "options": [
        "<p>B, C and E Only</p>\n",
        "<p>A, C and E Only</p>\n",
        "<p>B, C and D Only</p>\n",
        "<p>A, D and E Only</p>"
      ],
      "correctOption": 0,
      "correctAnswer": null,
      "questionType": "MCQ",
      "marks": 4,
      "negativeMarks": -1,
      "subject": "Chemistry",
      "topic": "haloarenes",
      "difficulty": "Easy",
      "solution": "<p>In chlorocyclohexane, chlorine shows only the $-\\mathrm{I}$ (electron-withdrawing inductive) effect.</p>\n<p>So, the $\\mathrm{C}-\\mathrm{Cl}$ bond remains a normal single bond and is more polar (more electron density is pulled towards chlorine).</p>\n<p>In chlorobenzene, chlorine shows two effects: $-\\mathrm{I}$ and $+\\mathrm{M}$ (lone pair donation by resonance into the benzene ring).</p>\n<p>Because $-\\mathrm{I}>+\\mathrm{M}$, the bond is still polar, but the $+\\mathrm{M}$ effect reduces the polarity compared to chlorocyclohexane.</p>\n<p>The $+\\mathrm{M}$ effect also causes resonance between chlorine lone pairs and the aromatic ring, which gives the $\\mathrm{C}-\\mathrm{Cl}$ bond partial double bond character.</p>",
      "section": "A",
      "instruction": "",
      "examSource": "jee-main"
    },
